    The Arts Crowd was Here in the 1920s
    This neighborhood features classic and historic restaurants, places where famous writers and artists hung out in the 1920s. It is also dominated by a huge busy train station. Wander some of the side streets and look for buildings that feature artist lofts. Nice place to visit, nice place to live.

    Artists and Writers in the 1920s
    We met our friend here for dinner. The neighborhood is well-served by the Metro and has a lot of classic cafes and bistros, plus the huge train station. This area was famous as a hang-out for artists and writers in the 1920s as everyone had a favorite cafe. If you walk around you may spot some apartment buildings with artists studios built in, as there was so much demand.

Not a must for first time visitors
Dec 2019
The Luxembourg gardens is where the prime tourist area ends in this part of Paris.
Going further south you enter the Montparnasse neighborhood which hasn't that much to offer to tourists. It's rather a residential - living and working area.
Main attractions here include an old and big cemetery and the Montparnasse tower observation deck on the top floor of the highest bldg in central Paris (see that review).
